# Normalize the data by removing anything above 2 std deviations using the z-score of each respective column
# I chose 2 std deviations becuase this is what I was taught in my statistics class is normal.
# We can switch to three if we want.
# 2 std deviations = 95% of data
# 3 std deviations = 99.7% of data
std_dev_cutoff = 2
bodyfat = bodyfat[(np.abs(stats.zscore(bodyfat[all_feats])) < std_dev_cutoff).all(axis=1)]

Model Selection And Training¶

Linear Regression¶

In [ ]:
# These will be used for the remainder of the notebook
n_folds = 10
scoring = 'neg_mean_squared_error'
In [ ]:
# Defining Learning Model
models = [
    (LinearRegression(), 'LinearReg')
]

for model, model_name in models:
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    accuracy=model.score(X_test, y_test)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring,cv=n_folds)
    
    # make predictions on the testing set
    y_pred= model.predict(X_test)
    
    print("%s\t| Accuracy=%f Mean=%f STD=%f" % (model_name, accuracy, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std()))
    print('\t\t| Mean squared error: %.2f' % mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print('\t\t| Root Mean squared error: %.2f' % np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
    print("\t\t| y= a + bx -> a=model.intercept_=%f b=model.coef_=%f" %(model.intercept_, model.coef_))
# end for

# Everything except target variable
X = bodyfat.drop('BodyFat', axis=1)

# Target variable
y = bodyfat['BodyFat'].values

# Split the dataset
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=42)

# Defining Learning Model
models = [
    (LinearRegression(), 'MultiLinearReg'),
    (KNeighborsRegressor(), 'KNNeighbors')
]

for model, model_name in models:
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    accuracy=model.score(X_test, y_test)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring,cv=n_folds)
   
    # make predictions on the testing set
    y_pred= model.predict(X_test)
    
    print("%s\t| Accuracy=%f Mean=%f STD=%f" % (model_name, accuracy, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std()))
    print('\t\t| Mean squared error: %.2f' % mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print('\t\t| Root Mean squared error: %.2f' % np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))

    plt.figure(figsize=(20,6))
    plt.plot(y_test, color='orange', marker='o', label='Actual')
    plt.plot(y_pred, 'gs', label=model_name)

    plt.tick_params(axis='x', which='both', bottom=False, top=False, labelbottom=False)
    plt.ylabel('Target')
    plt.xlabel('Training samples')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0.)
    plt.title('Regressor predictions and their average')

    plt.show()
# end for

Fine-tuning The Model¶

In [ ]:
# Train classifiers
# Create a gradient boosting regressor, a random forest regressor and a linear regression. 
# Then, we will use the 3 regressors to build the voting regressor:

gbr = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=1)
rfr = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=1)
mlr = LinearRegression()
ereg = VotingRegressor([('gb', gbr), ('rf', rfr), ('mlr', mlr)])

# Defining Learning Model
models = [
    (mlr, 'MLinearReg'),
    (gbr, 'GradientBReg'),
    (rfr,'RandomForestReg'),
    (ereg,'EnsembleReg')
]

for model, model_name in models:
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    accuracy=model.score(X_test, y_test)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring,cv=n_folds)
    
    # make predictions on the testing set
    y_pred= model.predict(X_test)
    
    print("%s\t| Accuracy=%f Mean=%f STD=%f" % (model_name, accuracy, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std()))
    print('\t\t| Mean squared error: %.2f' % mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print('\t\t| Root Mean squared error: %.2f' % np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
# end for

Fine tuning our model using ensemble regression (voting regression) yielded the best results as of yet with a solid 99.9% accuracy rating. Lets see if we can't fine tune our dataset at the same time by calculating the feature importance value of each feature.

In [ ]:
# Everything except target variable
X = bodyfat.drop('BodyFat', axis=1)

# Target variable
y = bodyfat['BodyFat'].values

param_grid = [
    # try 12 (34) combinations of hyperparameters
    {'n_estimators': [3, 10, 30], 'max_features': [2, 4, 6, 8]},
    # then try 6 (23) combinations with bootstrap set as False
    {'bootstrap': [False], 'n_estimators': [3, 10], 'max_features': [2, 3, 4]},
  ]

forest_reg = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)
# train across 5 folds, that's a total of (12+6)*5=90 rounds of training 
grid_search = GridSearchCV(forest_reg, param_grid, cv=5,
                           scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
                           return_train_score=True)
grid_search.fit(X, y)

param_distribs = {
        'n_estimators': stats.randint(low=1, high=200),
        'max_features': stats.randint(low=1, high=8),
    }

forest_reg = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)
rnd_search = RandomizedSearchCV(forest_reg, param_distributions=param_distribs,
                                n_iter=10, cv=5, scoring=scoring, random_state=42)
rnd_search.fit(X, y)

feature_importances = grid_search.best_estimator_.feature_importances_

feat_importance_tuples = sorted(zip(feature_importances, all_feats), reverse=True)

top_feats = ['Density', 'Abdomen', 'Chest', 'Hip', 'Weight']
top_feats_agg_importance = 0
reg_feats_agg_importance = 0

for importance_value, feat_name in feat_importance_tuples:
    if feat_name in top_feats:
        top_feats_agg_importance += importance_value
    else:
        reg_feats_agg_importance += importance_value
    # end if
# end for

# Split the dataset
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=42)

# Defining Learning Model
models = [
    (LinearRegression(), 'MultiLinearReg'),
    (KNeighborsRegressor(), 'KNNeighbors')
]

for model, model_name in models:
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    accuracy=model.score(X_test, y_test)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring,cv=n_folds)
   
    # make predictions on the testing set
    y_pred= model.predict(X_test)
    
    print("%s\t| Accuracy=%f Mean=%f STD=%f" % (model_name, accuracy, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std()))
    print('\t\t| Mean squared error: %.2f' % mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print('\t\t| Root Mean squared error: %.2f' % np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))

    plt.figure(figsize=(20,6))
    plt.plot(y_test, color='orange', marker='o', label='Actual')
    plt.plot(y_pred, 'gs', label=model_name)

    plt.tick_params(axis='x', which='both', bottom=False, top=False, labelbottom=False)
    plt.ylabel('Target')
    plt.xlabel('Training samples')
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', borderaxespad=0.)
    plt.title('Regressor predictions and their average')

    plt.show()
# end for

X = tuned_df.drop('BodyFat', axis=1)

# Target variable

# Split the dataset
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=42)

# Train classifiers
# Create a gradient boosting regressor, a random forest regressor and a linear regression. 
# Then, we will use the 3 regressors to build the voting regressor:

gbr = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=1)
rfr = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=1)
mlr = LinearRegression()
ereg = VotingRegressor([('gb', gbr), ('rf', rfr), ('mlr', mlr)])

# Defining Learning Model
models = [
    (mlr, 'MLinearReg'),
    (gbr, 'GradientBReg'),
    (rfr,'RandomForestReg'),
    (ereg,'EnsembleReg')
]

for model, model_name in models:
    model.fit(X_train,y_train)
    accuracy=model.score(X_test, y_test)
    cv_results = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring,cv=n_folds)
    
    # make predictions on the testing set
    y_pred= model.predict(X_test)
    
    print("%s\t| Accuracy=%f Mean=%f STD=%f" % (model_name, accuracy, cv_results.mean(), cv_results.std()))
    print('\t\t| Mean squared error: %.2f' % mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    print('\t\t| Root Mean squared error: %.2f' % np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)))
# end for

Using ensemble regression with the newly tuned dataset, we see that we have a minor drop in our accuracy, but it is still at 99.9%. Even though there was a small drop in acuracy, the benfit of using a cleaner more concise version of the datset can not be overlooked or dismissed. This holds especially true when considering the incredible accuracy gain when using the KNN model.

Using the metrics from the ensemble regression we can also see that there is no need to do ensemble regression with the tuned dataset since multi-linear regression actually outperforms ensemble regression.
